Fig. 309
).

Sexually dimorphic characters
. Male with very weakly developed mesotrochanteric and mesofemoral brushes of setae. Male with pro- and mesobasotarsomeres (
Fig. 302
) only somewhat expanded compared with female (
Fig. 303
), both male and female with protarsomere III relatively elongate (
Figs 302A, 303A
), but slightly longer in female (
Fig. 303A
).
